# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artuqids
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After receiving the permission of Sultan Mehmed V to form a new government in late October 1912, Kâmil Pasha sat down to engage in diplomatic talks with Bulgaria after the unsuccessful First Balkan War.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] With the Bulgarian demand for the cession of the former Ottoman capital city of Adrianople (today, and in Turkish at the time, known as Edirne) looming and the outrage among the Turkish populace as well as the CUP leadership, the CUP carried out the coup on January 23, 1913.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the coup, opposition parties were subject to heavy repression.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The new government led by Mahmud Şevket Pasha with Unionist support withdrew the Ottoman Empire from the ongoing London Peace Conference and resumed the war against the Balkan states to recover Edirne and the rest of Rumelia, but to no avail.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After his assassination in June, the CUP would take full control of the empire, and opposition leaders would be arrested or exiled to Europe.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The coup occurred in the context of toxic partisanship in the Ottoman Empire between the CUP and the Freedom and Accord Party, coming after a fraudulent general election and another coup the year before.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] During the coup, the Minister of War, Nazım Pasha, was killed and the Grand Vizier, Kâmil Pasha, was forced to resign.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The government fell into the hands of the CUP, now under the leadership of the triumvirate known as the "Three Pashas", made up of Enver, Talât, and Cemal Pasha.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Ottoman victory in the Second Balkan War and the recovery of Edirne in the face of pressure by the Entente powers moved the CUP closer to Germany ahead of World War I.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] In the 1908 elections, the Committee of Union and Progress (CUP) had only managed to win about 60 of the 288 seats in the Chamber of Deputies (Turkish: *Meclis-i Mebusân*), the popularly elected lower house of the General Assembly.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Nevertheless, it was the largest party in the Chamber.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Freedom and Accord Party (Liberal Union/Entente) was founded on 21 November 1911 by those in opposition to the CUP, and immediately attracted 70 Deputies to its ranks.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Only 20 days after its formation, Freedom and Accord won the December 1911 by-elections conducted in Constantinople by one vote.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The ruling CUP, seeing the potential of Freedom and Accord to win next year's general elections, took several precautions.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Hoping to thwart the nascent party's efforts to grow its ranks and better organize itself, the CUP asked Sultan Mehmed V to dissolve the Chamber and announced its call for early general elections in January 1912.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The fraud included early balloting, secret counting and reporting of votes, ballot stuffing, reapportioning electoral districts, and more, although the CUP still enjoyed genuine support outside of the cities.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The results of the elections had CUP win 269 of 275 seats in the Chamber, with Freedom and Accord only netting 6 Deputies.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Angered at their loss in the election, the leadership of Freedom and Accord sought extra-legal methods to regain power over the CUP, complaining vocally about electoral fraud.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At around this time, a group of military officers, uncomfortable with injustices it perceived within the military, organized itself into an armed organization known as the "Savior Officers" (Turkish: *Halâskâr Zâbitân*) and made their presence known to the imperial government.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Savior Officers, quickly becoming partisans of Freedom and Accord, soon created unrest in the capital Constantinople.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After gaining the support of Prince Sabahaddin, another opposition leader, the Savior Officers published public declarations in newspapers.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Finally, after giving a memorandum to the Military Council, the Savior Officers succeeded in getting Grand Vizier Mehmed Said Pasha (who they blamed for allowing the early elections that led to the CUP domination of the Chamber) and his government of CUP ministers to resign in July 1912.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the Savior Officers had succeeded in making sure that the Great Cabinet was free of CUP members, the CUP's domination of the Chamber of Deputies had not changed.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Soon, however, rumors began to circulate that the government would dissolve the Chamber of Deputies and call new elections.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The rumors were confirmed when, a few days after Ahmed Muhtar Pasha took office, the Savior Officers sent another memorandum, this time to the President of the Chamber of Deputies (and CUP member), Halil Bey, demanding that the Chamber be dissolved for new elections within 48 hours.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP members in the Chamber condemned and censured this threat.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] However, thanks to a law he had passed through the Senate, Ahmed Muhtar Pasha was able, with the sultan's support, to dissolve the Chamber with ease on 5 August, after which Sultan Mehmed V immediately called for new elections by imperial decree.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] While preparations for new elections were underway, however, the First Balkan War erupted early in October 1912, catching Ahmed Muhtar Pasha's administration off-guard.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the foreign crisis in the Balkans put a temporary halt to domestic politics, it did not stop them.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Unlike his predecessor Ahmed Muhtar Pasha, who had been non-partisan, Kâmil Pasha was an ardent anti-Unionist and was determined to use his premiership to destroy the CUP.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After 1 January 1913 when the party came under the control of Gümülcineli İsmail, he saw both the CUP and Freedom and Accord as dangerous revolutionary committees.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Using his friendly relations with the British, Kâmil Pasha also sat down to end the ongoing First Balkan War diplomatically.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] However, the heavy Ottoman military defeats during the war continued to sap morale, as rumors that the capital would have to be moved from Constantinople to inland Anatolia spread.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Bulgarian Army had soon advanced as far as Çatalca, a western district of modern Istanbul.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At this point, Kâmil Pasha's government signed an armistice with Bulgaria in December 1912 and sat down to draw up a treaty for the end of the war at the London Peace Conference.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Great Powers–the British Empire, France, Italy, and Russia–had begun to engage in the relationship of Bulgaria with the Ottoman Empire, citing the 1878 Treaty of Berlin.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Great Powers gave a note to the Sublime Porte (the Ottoman government) that they wanted the Ottoman Empire to cede Adrianople (Edirne) to Bulgaria and the Aegean islands under its control, most of which by that time had been captured by the Greek Navy, to the Great Powers themselves.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Because of the losses experienced by the army so far in the war, the Kâmil Pasha government was inclined to accept the "Midye-Enez Line" as a border to the west and, while not outright giving Edirne to Bulgaria, favored transferring control of it to an international commission.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the capture of Salonica (Thessaloniki), the birthplace of many progressive political leaders and movements of the era, by Greece in November 1912, many CUP members were arrested by Greek forces and exiled to Anatolia.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At the same time, Freedom and Accord found itself on the brink of dissolution after intra-party conflicts.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Left with little political power and flexibility, the CUP began to plan a coup against Kâmil Pasha's government.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] In addition, an animosity had already been brewing between Kâmil Pasha and the CUP since the 1908 Young Turk Revolution that had started the Second Constitutional Era.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] During the more than four years since, Kâmil Pasha had made a series of efforts to keep CUP members far from government and keep the army, which had many CUP members among its ranks, out of politics.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] By January 1913, the CUP was thoroughly frustrated with Kâmil Pasha.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the coup was to be a surprise attack, the CUP had made definitive decisions to carry it out far in advance.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although he was killed during the coup, both the CUP and Freedom and Accord claimed that they had been planning to give Minister of the Navy Nazım Pasha a position in their next cabinet.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP's Talaat Bey went as far as to say some time after the coup that the CUP had previously offered Nazım Pasha the position of grand vizier and the leadership its cabinet.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At this time, Talaat Bey (later known as Talaat Pasha) also began to make his way towards the Sublime Porte with a group of CUP loyalists.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] When Enver Bey arrived in front of the Ministry of Public Works (Turkish: *Nafıa Nazırlığı*) building, fellow CUP members Ömer Naci and Ömer Seyfettin were already provoking a crowd that had gathered by loudly proclaiming that Kâmil Pasha was about to cede Adrianople to the Bulgarians.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The speeches made by Ömer Naci and Ömer Seyfettin were effective, and the front of the Sublime Porte was soon filled with a crowd shouting slogans against Kâmil Pasha's government.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Moreover, up to 60 CUP members were placed around the Sublime Porte's buildings.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Enver Bey, along with confederates Talaat Bey, Sapancalı Hakkı, Yakub Cemil, Mustafa Necip, and about 50 others, entered the Sublime Porte compound of government buildings and made their way into the Grand Vizier's building, in which Kâmil Pasha and his cabinet were in session.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] An aide-de-camp to the Grand Vizier, Ohrili Nâfiz Bey, heard the commotion and opened fire on the raid party but was unable to hit any of them.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Himself wounded in the exchange, Ohrili Nâfiz Bey hid in the aide-de-camp office; when Mustafa Necip entered the office, Ohrili Nâfiz Bey shot and killed him but died himself of his wounds sustained from Mustafa Necip.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] An aid-de-camp and nephew of Nazım Pasha, Kıbrıslı Tevfik Bey, had also drawn his revolver and fired at the raid party, his bullet also striking Mustafa Necip.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the raiders returned fire, Kıbrıslı Tevfik Bey was instantly killed.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] During the shooting, a secret police agent and an attendant of the Sheikh ul-Islam were also killed.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Hearing the gunshots, Minister of War Nazım Pasha stepped out of his room and rushed towards the raid party.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] According to the memoirs of future Turkish president and prime minister Celâl Bayar, Nazım Pasha angrily shouted at the men, "What is going on?
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] You came to raid the grand vizier's office?", using "ill-mannered" profanities in his rage, after which Enver Bey saluted him and tried to explain his intentions.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At this time Yakub Cemil, approaching Nazım Pasha from the back while he was engaged with Enver Bey and the rest of the coup party, fired his gun at Nazım Pasha's right temple, killing him.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Another account claimed that Enver Bey had tried to stop Yakup Cemil from killing Nazım Pasha, but Yakup Cemil had refused to listen.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Yet another version of events held that either Enver Bey or Talaat Bey had accidentally killed Nazım Pasha while trying to protect themselves from gunfire from his aid-de-camp Kıbrıslı Tevfik Bey.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] In any case, the CUP termed Nazım Pasha's death during the coup a "regrettable accident", saying that it was unpremeditated but "unavoidable" under the circumstances.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP said that the fact Interior Minister Ahmet Reşit had been allowed to go unhurt proved that the coup leaders had desired to avoid bloodshed, since Ahmet Reşit was much more hostile towards the CUP than Nazım Pasha was.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After this, Enver and Talaat Bey entered Grand Vizier Kâmil Pasha's room and forced him to write a letter of resignation at gunpoint.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After Kâmil Pasha finished writing, Enver Bey immediately left the Sublime Porte to deliver the letter to Sultan Mehmed V in his palace, driving to the palace in the Sheikh ul-Islam's (Şeyhülislam) car.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Kâmil Pasha was replaced as Grand Vizier and Nazım Pasha as Minister of War by Mahmud Shevket Pasha, who took both posts.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the CUP appointed Grand Vizier Mahmud Shevket Pasha to lead their cabinet, he was genial towards the opposition Freedom and Accord Party.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] When one of Nazım Pasha's relatives assassinated him in revenge in June 1913, the CUP used the opportunity to crack down on the opposition.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Twelve men held responsible by the CUP for Mahmud Shevket Pasha's death, including Nazım Pasha's relative, were convicted for murder and hanged.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The opposition parties, already sidelined by the coup, were heavily repressed by the CUP.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The leaders of the Savior Officers (Turkish: *Halâskâr Zâbitân*) escaped to Egypt and Albania.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Another opposition leader Prince Sabahaddin, who had backed the Savior Officers against the CUP, fled to western Switzerland, where he would remain until 1919.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Freedom and Accord partisans would attempt several plots against the Unionist government until the outbreak of World War I.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The party would regain some semblance of power in the Armistice Era after World War I, though again fell into infighting under Colonel Sadık's chairmanship.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The coup essentially led to the establishment of a dictatorial triumvirate known as the "Three Pashas": the soon-to-be war minister, Enver Pasha, the soon-to-be interior minister, Talaat Pasha, and the soon-to-be naval minister, Cemal Pasha.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Three Pashas, leading the CUP autocratically, would control the Empire until fleeing the country at the end of World War I.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The coup is considered one of the first violent coups d'état to take place in modern Turkish history, seen as some as establishing a precedent for future coups in the Republic of Turkey.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Though initially opposed in principle to the extension of local autonomy to the provinces, the CUP now seemed inclined to reconcile with those in favor of greater extension of the millet system to enable Ottoman Muslim unity.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP government introduced several political and military reforms to the empire, including increasing centralization and carrying out military modernization efforts.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Under coup leader Enver Bey (later Pasha), the Ottoman Empire moved towards a closer relationship with the German Empire, officially leading to the German–Ottoman alliance being ratified the next year in 1914.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Enver would enter the empire into World War I that same year as part of the Central Powers, on the side of Germany, in contrast to the overthrown Kâmil Pasha, who was partial towards the British.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The first major offensive the Turks undertook in World War I was an unsuccessful attempt to drive the Russians from the portion of Western Armenia they had taken in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the failure of this expedition, the CUP's leaders, Enver, Cemal, and Talaat, were involved in ordering the deportations and massacres of 1 and 1.5 million Armenians in 1915–1916 in what became known as the Armenian genocide.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After World War I and the signing of the armistice of Mudros, the leadership of the Committee of Union and Progress and selected former officials were court-martialled with/including the charges of subversion of the constitution, wartime profiteering, and the massacres of both Armenians and Greeks.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The court reached a verdict which sentenced the organizers of the massacres, Talat, Enver, Cemal and others to death.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The public support for the coup was questioned at the time by analysts, some of whom reported that the CUP was backed by only a small crowd of actual citizens who had been gathered only within the hour by provocative speeches made by CUP members.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Eyewitnesses and newspapers reported very little actual popular participation in the coup or the events surrounding it.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Rémond said that preventing the minimalist coup would have taken at most 50 guards, and that the only reason that the Sublime Porte had been defenseless was because Kâmil Pasha wanted to call the bluff of any real threat the CUP, which he had sidelined politically, posed to his government.
[src:artuqids/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the coup, Rémond said, he found the capital Constantinople to be quiet and devoid of public opinion, whether about the coup or the ongoing First Balkan War, noting an air of "indifference" among not only the populace, but the statesmen involved themselves.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The **Abbasid dynasty**, or **Abbasids**, (Arabic: بنو العباس, romanized: *Banu al-ʿAbbās*) was an Arab dynasty that ruled the third Islamic caliphate between 750 and 1258.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] They were from the Qurayshi Hashimid clan of Banu Abbas, descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasid Caliphate is divided into three main periods: Early Abbasid era (750–861), Middle Abbasid era (861–936) and Later Abbasid era (936–1258).
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] A cadet branch of the dynasty also ruled as ceremonial rulers for the Mamluk Sultanate (1261–1517) until their conquest by the Ottoman Empire.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasids descended from Muhammad's uncle Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib (566–653 CE), an early Qur'an scholar from whom the dynasty takes its name.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Their roots trace back to Hashim ibn 'Abd Manaf and Adnan.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasid dynasty ruled the third caliphate to succeed the Islamic prophet Muhammad.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasids ruled for most of the caliphate from their capital in Baghdad, Iraq after having overthrown the Umayyad Caliphate in the Abbasid Revolution of 750 CE (132 AH).
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasid Caliphate first centered its government in Kufa, Iraq, but in 762 the caliph Al-Mansur founded the city of Baghdad near the ancient city of Babylon over the ruins of the ancient Sassanid capital of Ctesiphon.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Baghdad became the center of science, culture and innovation, housing several key academic institutions like the House of Wisdom, in what became known as the Golden Age of Islam.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] It was during this early period, in particular during the governance of Al-Mansur, Harun al-Rashid, and al-Ma'mun, that its reputation and power were created.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Mu'tasim moved the capital away from Baghdad to the new city of Samarra.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasid Caliphate was at its peak until the assassination of Caliph Al-Mutawakkil in 861.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Mutawakkil had appointed his oldest son, al-Muntasir, as his heir in 849/50, but slowly had shifted his favour to his second son, al-Mu'tazz, encouraged by al-Fath ibn Khaqan and the vizier Ubayd Allah ibn Yahya ibn Khaqan.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] This rivalry extended into the political sphere, as al-Mu'tazz's succession appears to have been backed by the traditional Abbasid elites as well, while al-Muntasir was backed by the Turkic and *Maghariba* guard troops.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] In late autumn 861, matters came to a head: in October, al-Mutawakkil ordered the estates of the Turkic general Wasif to be confiscated and handed over to al-Fath.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Feeling backed into a corner, the Turkic leadership began a plot to assassinate the Caliph.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Even worse, according to al-Tabari, on the next day al-Mutawakkil alternately vilified and threatened to kill his eldest son, and even had al-Fath slap him on the face.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] With rumours circulating that Wasif and the other Turkish leaders would be rounded up and executed on 12 December, the conspirators decided to act.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] According to al-Tabari, a story later circulated that al-Fath and Ubayd Allah were forewarned of the plot by a Turkic woman, but had disregarded it, confident that no-one would dare carry it out.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] On the night of 10/11 December, about one hour after midnight, the Turks burst into the chamber where the Caliph and al-Fath were having supper.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Fath was killed trying to protect the Caliph, who was killed next.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muntasir, who now assumed the Caliphate, initially claimed that al-Fath had murdered his father, and that he had been killed after; within a short time, however, the official story changed to al-Mutawakkil choking on his drink.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The murder of al-Mutawakkil began the tumultuous period known as "Anarchy at Samarra", which lasted until 870 and brought the Abbasid Caliphate to the brink of collapse.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The decline of the Abbasids started with the death of al-Mutawakkil.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] After his assassination, the Anarchy at Samarra began.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] This was a period of extreme internal instability marked by the violent succession of four caliphs from 861 to 870.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muntasir became Caliph on 11 December 861, after his father al-Mutawakkil was assassinated by members of his Turkic guard.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Although he was suspected of being involved in the plot to kill al-Mutawakkil, he was able to quickly take control of affairs in Samarra and receive the oath of allegiance from the leading men of the state.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muntasir's sudden elevation to the Caliphate served to benefit several of his close associates, who gained senior positions in the government after his ascension.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Included among these were his secretary, Ahmad ibn al-Khasib, who became vizier, and Wasif, a senior Turkic general who had likely been heavily involved in al-Mutawakkil's murder.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] His reign lasted less than half a year; it ended with his death from unknown causes on Sunday, 7 June 862, at the age of 24 years.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] 861–862), the Turks pressured him into removing al-Mu'tazz and al-Mu'ayyad from the succession.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] When al-Muntasir died, the Turkic officers gathered together and decided to install the dead caliph's cousin al-Musta'in (son of al-Mutawakkil's brother Muhammad) on the throne.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The new caliph was almost immediately faced with a large riot in Samarra in support of the disenfranchised al-Mu'tazz; the rioters were put down by the military but casualties on both sides were heavy.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Musta'in, worried that al-Mu'tazz or al-Mu'ayyad could press their claims to the caliphate, first attempted to buy them off and then threw them in prison.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] In 866 his nephew al-Musta'in was killed by al-Mu'tazz after Fifth Fitna.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Mu'tazz's reign marks the apogee of the decline of the Caliphate's central authority, and the climax of centrifugal tendencies, expressed through the emergence of the autonomous dynasties in Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Finally, unable to meet the financial demands of the Turkic troops, in mid-July a palace coup deposed al-Mu'tazz.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He was imprisoned and maltreated to such an extent that he died after three days, on 16 July 869.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He was succeeded by his cousin al-Muhtadi.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He ruled until 870, until he was murdered on 21 June 870, and replaced by his cousin, al-Mu'tamid (r.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] In a series of campaigns al-Mu'tadid recovered the provinces of Jazira, Thughur, and Jibal, and effected a rapprochement with the Saffarids in the east and the Tulunids in the west that secured their—albeit largely nominal—recognition of caliphal suzerainty.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] These successes came at the cost of gearing the economy almost exclusively towards the maintenance of the army, which resulted in the expansion and rise to power of the central fiscal bureaucracy and contributed to the Caliph's lasting reputation for avarice.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Mu'tadid was renowned for his cruelty when punishing criminals, and subsequent chroniclers recorded his extensive and ingenious use of torture.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] His reign saw the permanent move of the capital back to Baghdad, where he engaged in major building activities.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Mu'tadid had taken care to prepare his son and successor, al-Muktafi, for his role by appointing him as governor in Rayy and the Jazira.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Although al-Muktafi tried to follow his father's policies, he lacked his energy.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The heavily militarized system of al-Muwaffaq and al-Mu'tadid required the Caliph to actively participate in campaigns, setting a personal example and forming ties of loyalty, reinforced by patronage, between the ruler and the soldiers.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muktafi, on the other hand, did not "in his character and comportment [...], being a sedentary figure, instil much loyalty, let alone inspiration, in the soldiers" (Michael Bonner).
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] After al-Muktafi's death, al-Muqtadir came to the throne.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He came to the throne at the age of 13, the youngest Caliph in Abbasid history.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muqtadir's long reign (908–932) had brought the Abbasids to their lowest ebb, in which most of Northern Africa was lost.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Mosul had thrown off its dependence and the Byzantine Empire could make raids at pleasure along the poorly protected borders.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Yet in the East formal recognition of the Caliphate remained in place, even by those who virtually claimed their independence; and nearer home, the Qarmathians had been for the time put down.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] After Al-Muqtadir's death, al-Qahir came to power in 932.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He ruled for two years until he was pressured to abdicate in favour of Al-Muqtadir's nominated heir al-Radi (r.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] When he refused to abdicate, he was blinded and cast into prison.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] According to al-Mas'udi, al-Radi "kept news of him hidden" so that he vanished from common knowledge.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He was not freed until eleven years later, when al-Mustakfi (r.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] 944–946) came to the throne and discovered him locked away in a remote room in the palace.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Radi's reign marked the end of the Caliph's political power and the rise of military strongmen, who competed for the title of Amir al-umara.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muttaqi and his successors were all considered as *later* Abbasids.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muti was a weak figure, for all intents and purposes a puppet ruler of the Buyid emir, first Mu'izz al-Dawla, and then his son, Izz al-Dawla (r.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] As a result of his lack of real power, al-Muti' himself barely figures in the chronicles of his reign, and medieval historians generally considered his period as the lowest ebb of the Abbasid caliphate, an opinion shared by modern scholars as well.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Al-Muti was succeeded by his son al-Ta'i, who made attempts to restore his political authority until he was deposed by Baha al-Dawla.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He was succeeded by his cousin al-Qadir.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] In his long reign, al-Qadir was successful in restoring his political authority in Baghdad and its surrounding territory.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He was succeeded by his son al-Qa'im, and it was during his reign that the Buyids were replaced by the Seljuks.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Abbasids continued their partnership with the Seljuks until the reign of al-Muqtafi.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Then Abbasid continued to rule Iraq directly without disturbance until Mongol Invasion in 1258.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Mamluk Sultans of Egypt and Syria later appointed an Abbasid prince as Caliph of Cairo, but these Mamluk Abbasid Caliphs were marginalized and merely symbolic, with no temporal power and little religious influence.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The Cairo Abbasids were largely ceremonial Caliphs under the patronage of the Mamluk Sultanate that existed after the takeover of the Ayyubids.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Even though they kept the title for about 250 years more, other than installing the Sultan in ceremonies, these Caliphs had little importance.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] After the Ottomans conquered Egypt in 1517, the Caliph of Cairo, al-Mutawakkil III was transported to Constantinople.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Centuries later, a tradition developed saying that, at this time, al-Mutawakkil III formally surrendered the title of caliph as well as its outward emblems—the sword and mantle of Muhammad—to the Ottoman Sultan Selim I, establishing the Ottoman sultans as the new caliphal line.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] Some historians have noted that this story does not appear in the literature until the 1780s, suggesting that it was advanced to bolster the claims of caliphal jurisdiction over Muslims outside the empire, as asserted in the 1774 Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The rulers of the Kurdish emirate of Bahdinan, in present-day northern Iraq, reportedly claimed descent from the Abbasid caliphs.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] They originally established a local principality under the late Abbasid caliphs sometime around 1200.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The family remained in power under various circumstances until the 19th century, when the area was officially annexed to an Ottoman provincial administration.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] The rulers of the Wadai Empire claimed descent from the Abbasids in some traditions.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] They claimed descent from a man by the name of Salih ibn Abdullah ibn Abbas, whose father Abdullah was an Abbasid prince who fled Baghdad for the Hijaz upon the Mongol invasion.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He had a son named Salih who was invited to Sennar by some Muslim *ulama* while on pilgrimage in Mecca.
[src:artuqids/abbasid-dynasty] He is said to have continued to Wadai, where he converted the local people to Islam, after which they made him sultan, laying the foundations of the Wadai Empire.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The Ottoman Caliphate, the Muslim world's last widely recognized caliphate, was abolished on 3 March 1924 (R.C.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] 1342) by decree of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The process was one of Atatürk's reforms following the replacement of the Ottoman Empire with the Republic of Turkey.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Abdülmecid II was deposed as the last Ottoman caliph.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The caliph was nominally the supreme religious and political leader of all Sunni Muslims across the world.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] In the years prior to the abolition, during the ongoing Turkish War of Independence, the uncertain future of the caliphate provoked strong reactions among the worldwide community of Sunni Muslims.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The potential abolition of the caliphate had been actively opposed by the Indian-based Khilafat Movement, and generated heated debate throughout the Muslim world.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The 1924 abolition came about less than 18 months after the abolition of the Ottoman sultanate, prior to which the Ottoman sultan was *ex officio* caliph.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Mustafa Kemal Pasha (Atatürk) reportedly offered the caliphate to Ahmed Sharif as-Senussi, on the condition that he reside outside Turkey; Senussi declined the offer and confirmed his support for Abdülmecid.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] At least 13 different candidates were proposed for the caliphate in subsequent years, but none was able to gain a consensus for the candidacy across the Islamic world.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Candidates included Abdülmecid II, his predecessor Mehmed VI, King Hussein of Hejaz, Sultan Yusef of Morocco, King Amanullah Khan of Afghanistan, Imam Yahya of Yemen, and King Fuad I of Egypt.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Unsuccessful "caliphate conferences" were held in the Dutch East Indies (today Indonesia) in 1924, in 1926 in Cairo, and in 1931 in Jerusalem.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The Sharifian Caliphate under Hussein existed for a few years.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] In the late 19th century, Ottoman sultan Abdul Hamid II launched his pan-Islamist program in a bid to protect the Ottoman Empire from Western attack and dismemberment, and to crush the democratic opposition at home.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] He sent an emissary, Jamāl al-Dīn al-Afghānī, to British India in the late 19th century.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The cause of the Ottoman monarch evoked religious passion and sympathy amongst Indian Muslims.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] A large number of Muslim religious leaders began working to spread awareness and develop Muslim participation on behalf of the caliphate; of these, Maulana Mehmud Hasan attempted to organize a national war of independence against the British Raj with support from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Following the Ottoman defeat in World War I, the Ottoman sultan under Allied direction attempted to suppress nationalist movements, and secured an official fatwa from the Shaykh al-Islām declaring these to be un-Islamic.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] But the nationalists steadily gained momentum and began to enjoy widespread support.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Many sensed that the nation was ripe for revolution.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] In an effort to neutralize this threat, the sultan agreed to hold elections, with the hope of placating and co-opting the nationalists.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] To his dismay, nationalist groups swept the polls, prompting the Allied Powers to dissolve the General Assembly of the Ottoman Empire in April 1920.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] At the end of the Turkish War of Independence, the Turkish National Movement's Grand National Assembly voted to separate the caliphate from the sultanate and abolished the latter on 1 November 1922.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Initially, the National Assembly seemed willing to allow a place for the caliphate in the new regime and Mustafa Kemal did not dare to abolish the caliphate outright, as it still commanded a considerable degree of support from the common people.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The caliphate was symbolically vested in the House of Osman.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] On 19 November 1922, the Crown Prince Abdülmecid was elected caliph by the Turkish National Assembly at Ankara.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] He established himself in Istanbul (at that time Constantinople) on 24 November 1922.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] But the position had been stripped of any authority, and Abdülmecid's purely ceremonial reign would be short-lived.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] On 29 October 1923, the National Assembly declared Turkey a republic, and proclaimed Ankara its new capital.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] After over 600 years, the Ottoman Empire had officially ceased to exist.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Two Indian brothers, Mohammad Ali Jauhar and Maulana Shaukat Ali, leaders of the Indian-based Khilafat Movement, distributed pamphlets calling upon the Turkish people to preserve the Ottoman Caliphate for the sake of Islam.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] On 24 November 1923, Syed Ameer Ali and Aga Khan III sent a letter to İsmet Pasha (İnönü) on behalf of the movement.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Under Turkey's new nationalist government, however, this was construed as foreign intervention; any form of foreign intervention was labelled an insult to Turkish sovereignty and worse, a threat to state security.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Mustafa Kemal Pasha (Atatürk) promptly seized his chance.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] On his initiative, the National Assembly abolished the caliphate on 3 March 1924.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Abdülmecid was sent into exile along with the remaining members of the Ottoman House.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] With the failure of the Muslim world to find consensus on establishing a new caliphate, the claim of the caliphate entered a period of dormancy.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] In Egypt, debate focused on a controversial book by Ali Abdel Raziq which argued for secular government and against a caliphate.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] Today, two frameworks for pan-Islamic coordination exist: the Muslim World League and the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation, both of which were founded in the 1960s.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] The most active group that exists to re-establish the caliphate is Hizb ut-Tahrir, founded in 1953 as a political organization in then Jordanian-controlled Jerusalem by Taqiuddin al-Nabhani, an Islamic scholar and appeals court judge from Haifa.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-caliphate] War against the Islamic State brought an end to the Islamic State's short-lived caliphate.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Grand National Assembly of Turkey abolished the monarchy on 1 November 1922 and ended the Ottoman Empire, which had lasted from c.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] On 11 November 1922, at the Conference of Lausanne, the sovereignty of the Grand National Assembly exercised by the Government in Angora (now Ankara) over Turkey was recognized.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The last sultan, Mehmed VI, departed the Ottoman capital, Constantinople (now Istanbul), on 17 November 1922 aboard HMS *Malaya*.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The legal position was solidified with the signing of the Treaty of Lausanne on 24 July 1923 and the proclamation of the Republic of Turkey on 29 October 1923.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] In March 1924 the Caliphate was abolished, marking the end of the last remnant of the former monarchy.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Ottoman entry into World War I with the Central Powers occurred on 11 November 1914.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Middle Eastern theatre of World War I ended with the signing of the Armistice of Mudros on 30 October 1918.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Occupation of Istanbul by British, French and Italian forces occurred on 13 November 1918.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The partitioning of the Ottoman Empire began with the Treaty of London (1915) and continued with multiple agreements, mostly unilateral among the Allies.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] British troops began to occupy the key buildings of the Empire and arrest nationalists after the establishment of military rule on the night of 15 March 1920.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] On 18 March 1920 the Ottoman parliament met and sent a protest to the Allies that it was unacceptable to arrest five of its members.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] That was the last meeting of the body and marked the end of the Ottoman political system.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Sultan Mehmed VI dissolved the General Assembly of the Ottoman Empire on 11 April 1920.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Istanbul government, with the bureaucracy, but without the parliament, was left active with the Sultan as the decision maker.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Treaty of Sèvres on 10 August 1920 finalized the partitioning of the Empire.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] At the time, in waves, approximately 150 politicians were exiled to Malta.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Turkish national movement, led by Mustafa Kemal, established the Grand National Assembly of Turkey in Ankara on 23 April 1920.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Grand National Assembly of Turkey waged the Turkish War of Independence.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The war was against the monarchist Istanbul government.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Istanbul government, without a parliament, formed the Kuva-yi Inzibatiye, known as the "Army of the Caliphate", to fight against the Grand National Assembly's Kuva-yi Milliye.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Conflicts occurred at Bolu, Düzce, Hendek, Adapazarı, along with the other revolts during the Turkish War of Independence.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Caliphate army was sympathetic to the caliphate, hence the name, and armed by the British.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The strategic goal of the Caliphate army and of the British was to prevent the National Forces advancing towards the Bosporus straits.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Army of the Caliphate was defeated by the Kuva-yi Milliye.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Although the Kuva-yi Milliye was regarded as the first step of resistance in the liberation of Turkey, irregular warfare was abandoned later.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Before the Greek war began, Kuva-yi Milliye became the seed of an organized Turkish army, which then became the Turkish Armed Forces with the declaration of a Republic.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Ottoman Empire's sovereignty was embodied in the dynasty of Osman I, who was its founder and namesake.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] His family had ruled since 1299 in an unbroken lineage throughout the empire's history.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Ottoman sultan maintained supreme authority over the Ottoman Empire's polity.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The sultan was the empire's sole and absolute regent, head of state and head of government.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The grand viziers and polity established by the Ottoman Constitution functioned at the pleasure of the sultan.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] An Allied invitation was given to both the Constantinople and Ankara governments to appear at the Conference of Lausanne.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Mustafa Kemal was determined that only the Ankara government would be represented at the conference.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] On 1 November 1922, the Grand National Assembly declared that the Sultanate's Constantinople government was no longer the legal representative.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Grand National Assembly also resolved that Constantinople had not been the capital of the nation since its occupation by the Allies.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Furthermore, they declared that the Sultanate was to be abolished.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The abolition of the sultanate ended the Ottoman Empire.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] After hearing of the resolution, Mehmed VI sought refuge aboard the British warship *Malaya* on 17 November.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The remaining ministers in his government accepted the new political reality.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] There is no official document that declared the state capitulated by the Ottoman Government or sultan; the system resolved by itself.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Conference of Lausanne, on 11 November 1922, recognized the sovereignty of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey replacing the Ottoman Empire.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The last sultan, Mehmed VI, departed Constantinople on 17 November 1922.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] A list of 600 names to the Conference of Lausanne was presented, and were to be declared *personae non gratae*.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The list, which is a Who's Who of the Ottoman Empire, had the purpose of eliminating the ruling elite of the Ottomans.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Negotiations at Lausanne limited the number to 150, and the treaty was signed on 24 July 1923.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Ottoman dynasty embodied the Ottoman Caliphate since the sixteenth century, starting with the reign of Selim I.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The head of the Ottoman family kept the title caliph, power over all Muslims, as Mehmed's cousin Abdülmecid II took the title.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Ottoman dynasty was left as a political-religious successor to Muhammad and a leader of the entire Muslim community without borders in a post Ottoman Empire.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] Abdülmecid II's title was challenged in 1916 by the leader of the Arab Revolt King Hussein bin Ali of Hejaz, who denounced Mehmet V, but his kingdom was defeated and annexed by Ibn Saud in 1925.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] By 1922 most of the remaining inhabitants of Turkey were Muslims of either Turkish or Kurdish ethnicity.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] The Grand National Assembly of Turkey declared itself the Republic of Turkey on 29 October 1923.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] There were members of the Ottoman dynasty who were in Turkey after the declaration of the republic.
[src:artuqids/abolition-of-the-ottoman-sultanate] An exile list was also created and put into effect by the Republic of Turkey on 23 April 1924 (revised on 1 June 1924) which included the names of 120 adherents of the deposed Ottoman dynasty.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Turkey has a unitary structure in terms of administration and this aspect is one of the most important factors shaping the Turkish public administration.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] When three powers (executive, legislative and judiciary) are taken into account as the main functions of the state, local administrations have little power.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Turkey is a highly centralized unitary system, and the provinces are subordinated to the centre.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Local administrations were established to provide services in place and the government is represented by the governors and city governors.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Besides the governors and the city governors, other senior public officials are also appointed by the central government rather than appointed by mayors or elected by constituents.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Within this unitary framework, Turkey is subdivided into 81 provinces for administrative purposes.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Each province is divided into districts, for a total of 973 districts in the country.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Turkey is also subdivided into 7 regions and 21 subregions for geographic, demographic and economic purposes; this does not refer to an administrative division.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] The largely centralized structure of decision-making in Ankara is often considered an impediment to good governance, and causes resentment in particular in ethnic minority regions.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Steps towards decentralization since 2004 have proved to be a highly controversial topic in Turkey.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] Turkey is obligated under the European Charter of Local Self-Government to decentralize its administrative structure.
[src:artuqids/administrative-divisions-of-turkey] A decentralization program for Turkey is an ongoing discussion in the country's academics, politics and the broader public.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] The **Aegean region** (Turkish: *Ege Bölgesi*) is one of the seven geographical regions of Turkey.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] The largest city in the region is İzmir.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] Other big cities are Manisa, Aydın, Denizli, Muğla, Afyonkarahisar and Kütahya.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] Located in western Turkey, it is bordered by the Aegean Sea to the west, the Marmara region to the north, the Central Anatolia Region to the east, and the Mediterranean Region to the south.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] Among the four coastal regions, the Aegean Region has the longest coastline.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] The ecoregions of this region are all Terrestrial, more specifically Palearctic, and still more so, Mediterranean forests, woodlands, and scrub.
[src:artuqids/aegean-region] The climate of the Aegean Region has a Mediterranean climate at the coast, with hot, dry summers and mild to cool, wet winters and a semi-arid continental climate in the interior with hot, dry summers and cold, snowy winters.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In **Turkey, air pollution** kills more people than any other environmental issue.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Data from the World Health Organization (WHO) says 99% of the global population breathes unsafe air.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] No province in Turkey meets the WHO guidelines for clean air.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In 2024, more than 60,000 people in that country are estimated to have died from air-pollution-related illnesses.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Air pollution is particularly damaging to children's health.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Road transport and sometimes coal burning pollute towns and cities.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] There is no legal limit on fine particulates that cause lung and other diseases.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Cars and lorries spread diesel exhaust, dust, nitrogen oxides (NOx) and other fumes.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] There are no clean-air zones and tariffs on electric cars are higher than on cars with combustion engines.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Although electric-vehicle manufacturing and sales are increasing, policy is poorly co-ordinated, and as of 2023, health impact assessment is not done in Turkey.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Soot from the burning of wood for cooking and heating pollutes households and some cities.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Low-quality lignite coal, which is burnt in cities and in the oldest of the country's coal-fired power stations, is also a big part of the problem.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Some plant-specific pollution data is collected by the Environment Ministry but is not usually published.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2025, air quality in Turkey is below that of standards set by the European Union (EU).
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The civil-society organization Right to Clean Air Platform Turkey estimates the lack of a legal limit on fine particulates cost Turkey's economy 10% of gross domestic product (GDP) in 2024.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Air pollution has been shown to cause cancer, and to contribute to respiratory, cardiovascular and cerebrovascular diseases.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Asthma is expensive to treat and can be caused by exposure to nitrogen oxides.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] A study of air pollution and asthma in Niğde between 2006 to 2010 showed reporting of asthma cases was closely related to ambient sulfur dioxide (SO2) concentrations.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Daily variations in air pollutants were studied in Istanbul from 2013 to 2015 in relation to respiratory hospital admissions.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The air pollutants PM2.5, nitrogen dioxide (NO2), and PM10 were shown to increase the risk of hospital admissions for respiratory diseases.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Another study examined air pollutants and pediatric emergency-room visits to a tertiary hospital in Istanbul between January 2016 and December 2023.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] They reported increases in nitric oxide (NO), NOx, PM2.5, NO2, and PM10 were associated with more asthma-related pediatric visits to the emergency room.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Right to Clean Air Platform Turkey estimates one in seven deaths (68,000) in 2022 were due to air pollution.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Other estimates of annual excess mortality range from 37,000 due to PM2.5 to 60,000 from fossil-fuel use.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In many places, the health effects of air pollution cannot be estimated because there is not enough monitoring of PM10 and PM2.5 particulates; average early mortality, compared to if World Health Organization (WHO) air-pollution guidelines were followed, is estimated to be 0.4 years per person.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] This will vary by location because air pollution is more severe in some cities.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Air pollution in Turkey is a health risk mainly due to the burning of fossil fuels, such as coal and diesel.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2024, Turkey's National Energy Balance statistics do not split road-transport fuel into petrol and diesel.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2025, fewer than 5% of the country's cars were electric or hybrid, with diesel, petrol and liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) each over 30%.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Increasing the proportion of electric cars in use in Turkey to 10% by 2030 would also reduce the country's greenhouse-gas emmissions.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] There are high purchase taxes on new cars.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] There are no clean air zones and tariffs on electric cars are higher than on combustion cars.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Continued electrification of the rail network and high-speed line expansion are underway.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In 2022, most fine-particulate (PM2.5) pollution in Turkey came from residential combustion for cooking and heating.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Despite economic growth, the country's poorest families still use solid-biomass fuels such as wood, which pollutes some cities.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The use of these fuels increases indoor air pollution and is a health hazard; low-tier fuels are more harmful to human health.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Higher-income families may use modern fuels such as natural gas or electricity, which cause less pollution and can lead to better health outcomes.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Electricity supply, however, is often insufficient to meet a family's heating needs.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] If electricity is supplemented with low-quality biofuels, indoor air-pollution levels will increase and negatively affect health outcomes.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Women, children, and the elderly, who may spend more time indoors and deal with cooking, are most likely to suffer ill health due to indoor air pollution.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Income, education and home ownership are associated with use of higher-grade fuels for heating and cooking, and with better health.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] More than a quarter of adults in Turkey smoke tobacco; passive smoking is a danger and increases the risk of respiratory infection.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] This is below the recommended levels of the EU Industrial and Livestock Rearing Emissions Directive (IED 2.0).
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Air pollution is one of the environmental impacts of concrete.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Although asbestos was completely banned in 2010, it can still be a risk when older buildings are demolished, and in dumps.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In some rural areas of Turkey, deposits of regulated asbestos minerals and non-regulated fibrous minerals such as erionite naturally occur, increasing the risk of mesothelioma.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL) says pollution from coal-fired power stations causes significant illness and early deaths.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2025, legal action continues, as do allegations of inadequate filtering.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] According to Greenpeace Mediterranean, the coal-fired power plants in Afşin-Elbistan are the highest health risk in a European country, followed by Soma power station.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Wildfires and dust blown from the Sahara (PM10) sometimes pollute.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Levels of all types of pollutants across the country exceed World Health Organization guidelines.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Wood burning is a major source of indoor air pollution and contributes to outdoor air pollution.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Particulates from transport fuel use and tyre wear of vehicles are a danger to people's lungs.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Regulations in Turkey do not restrict particles less than 2.5 microns in diameter (PM2.5) , which cause lung diseases.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Although there is some monitoring of air pollution, many air pollution indicators are not available.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The country's air quality index omits particles smaller than 2.5 microns (PM2.5) but includes nitrogen dioxide, sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide, tropospheric ozone, and particles between 10 and 2.5 microns in diameter (PM10).
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] NO2 in cities such as Ankara is visible from satellites.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Diesel exhaust from vehicles contains NOx and other air pollutants.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Emissions of sulfur dioxide from coal-fired power stations are significant.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Volatile organic compounds (VOCs) come from some industries.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Emission levels of persistent organic pollutants are regulated but emission totals for these chemicals were not reported in 2019.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Ankara suffers from ground-level ozone pollution.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] There is ammonia pollution from agriculture.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Turkey emits about one percent of the world's greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Because most of the country's air pollution is caused by the burning of fossil fuels, Turkey's air pollution would be reduced by low emission zones for city traffic, and the replacement of free distribution of coal for poor families with a different support.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Climate-change mitigation would be a co-benefit of the main health benefits, and health improvement would be a co-benefit of climate-change mitigation.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] For example, the closure of Afşin A power plant to reduce carbon dioxide emissions would also reduce local air pollution and benefit the health of local residents.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In 2023, Right to Clean Air Platform Turkey said half of the 360 Ministry of Environment and Urbanization monitoring stations were not working properly.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Turkey has no pollutant release and transfer register law so there is no obligation for industry to publish pollution levels.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Turkey has not ratified the Gothenburg Protocol on air pollution.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Some industrial companies reach Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) 305 emissions standard.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] There is a pollutant release and transfer register, but as of September 2024 no years are publicly searchable because it is not yet technically complete, and it is unknown what exemptions will be granted or when the register will be completed.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2026 the http://www.kstk.gov.tr/ link which is supposed to be the register is not working.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Turkey has eight regional clean-air centres.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Many cities in Turkey are more polluted than typical European cities.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Some nearby cities are taking steps to counter pollution; Sofia, Bulgaria, is introducing a low-emission zone, and restricting the burning of coal and wood.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Pollution in Istanbul has lessened since the 1990s but traffic is still unhealthy.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] NO2 is visible in measurements by Orbiting Carbon Observatory 3.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Pollution worsens when high-pressure areas trap pollutants near the ground and prevent them from dispersing.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Most particles are ultrafine; researchers say ultrafine and black carbon should be continuously monitored.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2022, industry in Bursa is a particular problem.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] NO2 is visible in satellite measurements.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] A higher-than-average rate of multiple sclerosis (MS) may be related to local industry in Ereğli.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The Climate Change and Air Management Coordination Board is responsible for coordination between government departments.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] As of 2019, however, according to the EU, better-coordinated policies need to be established and implemented.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Turkey has not ratified the Gothenburg Protocol, although it has ratified the original Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution, and those reports are public.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Pollution from Turkey affects neighbouring countries.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The Armenian Nuclear Power Plant, 16 kilometres (9.9 miles) over the border, is old and said to be insufficiently earthquake proof.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In 2025 the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said poor air quality is a structural weakness in the economy.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The impact of air pollution on the economy via damage to health may be billions of euros.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] According to medical group Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL), reducing PM2.5 air pollution in Turkey would substantially increase GDP.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] According to the OECD, in 2019, the exemption of bitumen (asphalt) from special consumption tax was a subsidy of 5.9 billion lira.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In hot weather, bitumen, which is used for road surfaces, releases secondary organic aerosols, which can damage health.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In the Constitution of Turkey, Article 56 says: "Everyone has the right to live in a healthy and balanced environment.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The phasing out of coal is said to be essential.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The strengthening of environmental laws would benefit Turkey's economy.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] According to HEAL, over 500 premature deaths per year could be avoided by closing three power stations in Muğla.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Electric ferryboats have been proposed for the Bosphoros.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] A low-emission zone for road traffic has been suggested for Istanbul, and it has been suggested Turkey's vehicle tax system should be changed to better charge for pollution.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] More green space is suggested for cities.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The taxing of pollution by internal flights and a further improvement of the country's railways have also been suggested.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] The burning of wood indoors in Turkey has caused pollution since at least the Neolithic.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Lead was first smelted around 5,000 BC in Anatolia.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In 535 AD, Justinian I acknowledged the importance of clean air.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In the 19th century, air pollution was thought of in terms of miasma, the idea foul smells could cause disease.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Due to the high cost of oil after the 1970s oil crisis, cities increased the burning of lignite for residential heating.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] An Air Pollution Control Regulation was issued in the 1980s and the monitoring of air quality began in that decade.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] In early 2020, air pollution in most major cities in Turkey significantly decreased due to COVID-19 restrictions, but tropospheric ozone, a leading cause of smog, increased because fewer particles were available to block sunlight.
[src:artuqids/air-pollution-in-turkey] Air pollution started to rise again by the middle of the year.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The **Artuqid dynasty** (alternatively **Artukid**, **Ortoqid**, or **Ortokid**; Turkish: *Artuklu Beyliği, Artuklular*, pl.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] *Artukoğulları*) was established in 1102 as a Turkish principality of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] It formed a Turkoman dynasty rooted in the Oghuz Döger tribe, and followed the Sunni Muslim faith.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] It ruled in Northern Syria and Upper Mesopotamia in the eleventh through thirteenth centuries.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Artuqid dynasty took its name from its founder, Artuk Bey, who was a member of Döger branch of the Oghuz Turks and ruled one of the Turkmen principalities of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The dynasty was founded by Artuk, son of Eksük, a general originally under Malik-Shah I and then under the Seljuk emir of Damascus, Tutush I.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Tutush appointed Artuk governor of Jerusalem in 1086.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Artuk died in 1091, and was succeeded by his sons Sökmen and Ilghazi who were expelled from Jerusalem by the Fatimid vizier al-Afdal Shahanshah in 1098; the Fatimids lost the city to the Crusaders the following year after the siege of Jerusalem of 1099.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Sökmen and Ilghazi established themselves in Diyarbakır, Mardin, and Hasankeyf in al-Jazira where they came into conflict with the Seljuk sultanate.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Sökmen, bey of Mardin, defeated the Crusaders at the Battle of Harran in 1104.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Ilghazi succeeded Sökmen in Mardin and imposed his control over Aleppo at the request of the *qadi* Ibn al-Khashshab in 1118.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The next year, Ilghazi defeated the Crusader state Principality of Antioch at the Battle of Ager Sanguinis of 1119.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] After pillaging the County of Edessa, Ilghazi made peace with the Crusaders.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] In 1121, he went north towards Armenia with his son-in-law Mazyad Dubais II ibn Sadaqah and Sultan Malik of Ganja.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Ilghazi invaded Georgia and was defeated by David IV of Georgia at the Battle of Didgori of 1121.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Ilghazi died in 1122, and although his nephew Belek Ghazi nominally controlled Aleppo, the city was really controlled by ibn al-Khashshab.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Ibn al-Kashshab was murdered by Assassins in 1125, and Aleppo fell under the control of Zengi, atabeg of Mosul, in 1128.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] After the death of Belek Ghazi, the Artuqids were split between Harput, Hasankeyf and Mardin.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Sokman's son Rukn al-Dawla Dāʾūd, bey of Hasankeyf, died in 1144, and was succeeded by his son Kara Aslan.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Kara Aslan allied with Joscelin II of Edessa against the Zengids, and while Joscelin was away in 1144, Zengi recaptured Edessa, the first of the Crusader states to fall (see Siege of Edessa).
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Artuqids became vassals of the Zengids during the reign of Nur al-Din Zengi (r.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] 1146–1174), supporting the Zengids at the battle of Artah in 1164.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Kara Aslan's son Nūr al-Dīn Muḥammad allied with the Ayyubid sultan Saladin against Kilij Arslan II, Seljuk sultan of Rûm, whose daughter had married Nur ad-Din Muhammad.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] In the peace settlement with Kilij Arslan II, Saladin gained control of the Artuqid territory, even though the Artuqids were still technically vassals of Mosul, which Saladin did not control.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Seljuk Empire completely disintegrated soon after that in 1194.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Artuqid dynasty remained in nominal command of al-Jazira, but their power declined under Ayyubid rule.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Hasankeyf branch conquered Diyarbakır in 1198 and its center was moved here, but was demolished by the Ayyubids in 1231 when it attempted to form an alliance with the Seljuks.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Harput branch was destroyed by the Sultanate of Rum due to following a slippery policy between the Ayyubids and Seljuks.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Mardin branch survived for longer, but as a vassal of the Ayyubids, Sultanate of Rûm, Il-Khanate, Timurids and the Qara Qoyunlu.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Qara Arslan (r.1260–1292), ruler of Mardin, submitted to the Mongol Hulegu.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Qara Qoyunlu ruler Qara Mahammad invaded Mardin in 1384 and received the submission of its Artuqid ruler Majd al-Din Isa Al-Zahir (1376-1407).
[src:artuqids/artuqids] From this point onwards, the Artuqids operated as a vassal state of the Qara Qoyunlu.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Qara Qoyunlu captured Mardin and finally put an end to Artuqid rule in 1409.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Despite their constant preoccupation with war, members of the Artuqid dynasty left many architectural monuments.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Artuqid rulers commissioned many public buildings, such as mosques, bazaars, bridges, hospitals and baths for the benefit of their subjects.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] They left an important cultural heritage by contributing to literature and the art of metalworking.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The door and door handles of the great Mosque of Cizre are unique examples of Artuqid metal working craftsmanship, which can be seen in the Turkish and Islamic Arts Museum in Istanbul, Turkey.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] They made the most significant additions to Diyarbakır City Walls.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Urfa Gate was rebuilt by Muhammad, son of Kara Arslan.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] In the same area of the western wall, south of Urfa Gate, two imposing towers, Ulu Beden and Yedi Kardeş were commissioned in 1208 by the Artuqid ruler Nāṣir al-Dīn Maḥmūd who designed the Yedi Kardeş tower himself and apposed the Artuqid double-headed eagle on its walls.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] A large caravanserai in Mardin as well as the civil engineering feat of Malabadi Bridge are still in regular use in our day.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The partially standing Old Bridge, Hasankeyf, was built in 1116 by Kara Arslan.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Great Mosques of Mardin and Silvan were possibly but in any case considerably developed over the 12th century by several Artuqid rulers on the basis of existing Seljuk edifices.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The congregational mosque of Dunaysir (now Kızıltepe) was commissioned by Yülük Arslan (1184–1203) and completed after his death in 1204 by his brother Artuk Arslan (1203–1239).
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Artuqids are known for their sponsoring of literary works in Arabic.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] A copy of al-Sufi's book on astronomy *The Book of Fixed Stars*, a synthesis of Ptolemy's *Almagest* and Arabic astronomical traditions, was made in 1131 in Artuqid Mardin.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] 3493 in Kara Arslan (1148–1174 CE) commissioned a new Arabic translation of *De Materia Medica* by an Arab Christian author named Abu Salim al-Malti, probably from Malatya.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Ibn al-Azraq who worked as a *mutawalli ishraf al-waqf* for the Artuqids, wrote a historical chronicle called, *Tarīkh Mayyāfāriqīn*, concerning them and the Marwanids and Hamdanids.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Artuqid ruler Nasr al-Din Mahmud (r.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] 1201–1222) is known to have commissioned an edition of the *Al-Jāmi‘ fī ṣinā‘at al-ḥiyal* of Ibn al-Razzaz al-Jazari, devoted to the depiction of mechanical devices, in April 1206 at the Artuqid court (Ahmet III 3472, Topkapı Sarayı Library).
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The miniatures are thought to reflect various aspects of the Artuqid court at the time.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Ibn al-Razzaz al-Jazari was employed at the Artuqid court during the last quarter of the 12th century, and this is the earliest known manuscript of his opus.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Many of the figures in the manuscript wear the characteristic Turkic dress, with long coat and boots, and the *sharbush* headgear (of a special type seen only in Artuqid manuscripts, with a very tall cap behind the headplate and the limited usage of fur around the rim).
[src:artuqids/artuqids] An early edition of the *Maqamat al-Hariri* (Bibliothèque Nationale de France, Arabe 3929) is also considered as probably belonging to the same Artuqid school of painting.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The major branches of the Artuqid dynasty were those based in Hasankeyf, Harput, Mardin and Aleppo.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] This branch was initially based at Hasankeyf (Ḥiṣn Kaifā).
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The capital moved to Diyarbakır (Amid) in 1183.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Following the rule of Rukn al-Dīn Mawdūd, the territories of the Hasankeyf branch of the Artuqids were taken over by the Ayyubids.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Harput branch was initially part of the Hasankeyf branch until 1185, gaining independence from Kara Arslan.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Harput was conquered by Kayqubad I, Seljuk sultan of Rûm, in 1234.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Mardin branch of the Artuqids ruled in Mardin and Mayyafariqin from 1101–1409 and were primarily descendants of Ilghazi and his brother Alp-Yaruq.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Mardin was conquered by the Qara Qoyunlu, a Turkoman tribe, in 1409.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] The Artuqid branch that ruled Aleppo was an offshoot of the Mardin branch and included descendants of Ilghazi and his brothers Abd al-Jabar and Bahram ibn Artuk.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Aleppo was taken by Zengi in 1128 and ruled by the Zengid dynasty until 1183.
[src:artuqids/artuqids] Artuqids coinage was very figural, "with its apparent classical and Byzantine motifs and representations".
